  :prose
"Arcade DNA is the scoreboard. The number in the top-right corner is why
you keep playing. Every hit is +100. Two hits in the same 60-frame
window: ×2 multiplier — that hit was worth +200. Three in a row: ×3.
Miss, get hit, wait too long — the multiplier resets and the number
stops growing.

The whole feedback loop is: do a thing, see the number grow, WANT to
do the next thing to keep the number growing. Every arcade cabinet
ever built is a machine for growing that number. The number itself is
free — it's a variable. The magic is in the multiplier, the combo
timer, and how the number is DISPLAYED.

This chapter builds the scoreboard right. Base score. Combo counter
with a decay window. Multiplier that scales visibly with combo.
Number-that-grows visualization with `tick/ease`. Screen-flash on
combo-up. Persistent high score via Cortex.

---

## 13.1 Base score

Every hit is +100.

```scheme
(define score 0)

(define (basic-score)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 210)))
    (entity/shape! p 'triangle 8)
    (entity/hp! p 5)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -4 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 4 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (set! score (+ score 100))
         (world/camera-shake! 1 0.9))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 8 8)
       (paint-text (string-append \"Score: \" (number->string score))
                   10 10)))))

(big-bang basic-score)
```

You press 'a', score grows. That is enough to see the pattern. Now
add combo.

---

## 13.2 The combo counter

Successive hits within a window grow the combo.

```scheme
(define score 0)
(define combo 0)
(define combo-decay-at 0)     ;; frame at which combo resets

(define (combo-score)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 210)))
    (entity/shape! p 'triangle 8)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -4 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 4 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (set! combo (+ combo 1))
         (set! combo-decay-at (+ (world/frame) 60))  ;; 1 sec window
         (set! score (+ score (* 100 combo)))
         (world/camera-shake! (min 5 combo) 0.9))
       ;; Combo decay.
       (when (>= (world/frame) combo-decay-at)
         (set! combo 0))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 8 8)
       (paint-text (string-append \"Score: \" (number->string score)) 10 10)
       (paint-text (string-append \"x\" (number->string combo)) 10 20)))))

(big-bang combo-score)
```

Read the combo logic. Every 'a' press: bump combo, extend the decay
window to 60 frames from now, add `100 * combo` to score. If you
haven't pressed 'a' in a second, combo resets to 0 and the next hit
is worth just 100.

Kid presses 'a' rapidly: 100, 300, 600, 1000, 1500, 2100. Presses
'a' once, waits 2 seconds, presses again: 100, then 100. Same
five inputs, hugely different scores. That's the whole hook.

---

## 13.3 Growing number

The number should GROW when it changes. Not just update — visibly
scale up, then settle.

```scheme
(define score 0)
(define displayed-score 0)     ;; interpolates toward score
(define score-flash 0)          ;; frames of flash

(define (growing-score)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 210)))
    (entity/shape! p 'triangle 8)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -4 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 4 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (set! score (+ score 100))
         (set! score-flash 10))
       ;; Displayed-score chases actual score.
       (set! displayed-score
             (+ displayed-score
                (* 0.1 (- score displayed-score))))
       (when (> score-flash 0) (set! score-flash (- score-flash 1)))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 8 8)
       ;; Score painted big when flashing; normal otherwise.
       (paint-text (string-append \"Score: \"
                                  (number->string (round displayed-score)))
                   10
                   (if (> score-flash 0) 30 10))))))

(big-bang growing-score)
```

Two variables: `score` is the actual, `displayed-score` is the smooth
interpolation. Every frame, `displayed-score` gets 10% closer to
`score`. Hit 'a', score jumps 100, displayed-score smoothly climbs
from 0 to 100 over about 40 frames. That climb IS the dopamine.

The score-flash sets a position offset. When you hit, the text shifts
up 20 pixels for 10 frames, then returns. Subtle, effective. Real
arcade games do this AT SCALE — every hit, the number wobbles, glows,
bounces. Feel is code.

---

## 13.4 The multiplier

Combo doesn't just multiply the score — it multiplies the DISPLAY.
Bigger combo = bigger number on screen.

```scheme
(define score 0)
(define combo 0)
(define combo-decay-at 0)

(define (multiplier-display)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 210)))
    (entity/shape! p 'triangle 8)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -4 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 4 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (set! combo (+ combo 1))
         (set! combo-decay-at (+ (world/frame) 60))
         (set! score (+ score (* 100 combo))))
       (when (>= (world/frame) combo-decay-at)
         (set! combo 0))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 8 8)
       (paint-text (string-append \"Score: \" (number->string score)) 10 10)
       ;; Combo painted increasingly large, right-aligned.
       (when (> combo 0)
         (let ((y-off (- 30 (min combo 20))))
           (paint-text (string-append \"x\" (number->string combo))
                       (- 300 (* 8 (min combo 15))) y-off)))))))
(big-bang multiplier-display)
```

The combo number is painted in a size that grows with combo. At combo
5, subtly bigger. At combo 15, huge. At combo 20+, capped so it
doesn't take over the screen.

Every arcade game does something like this. The number is the reward
AND the punishment — when combo breaks, it disappears from the screen
entirely.

---

## 13.5 High-score persistence

Score should survive the game session.

```scheme
(define score 0)

(define (high-score-tracked)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((high-score (or (cortex/read 'arcade-high) 0))
        (p (world/spawn 'player 160 210)))
    (entity/shape! p 'triangle 8)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -4 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 4 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (set! score (+ score 100))
         (when (> score high-score)
           (set! high-score score)
           (cortex/write 'arcade-high score)))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 8 8)
       (paint-text (string-append \"Score: \" (number->string score)) 10 10)
       (paint-text (string-append \"High:  \" (number->string high-score))
                   10 20)))))

(big-bang high-score-tracked)
```

When score passes the high-score, we update the display AND persist.
Kid quits, comes back tomorrow: high score persists. The number the
kid is trying to beat is their own past self.

Even better: keep the top 5, not just top 1. Store as a Cortex list.
Show the leaderboard on the title screen (chapter 14).

---

## 13.6 The four patterns

**Composition.** Score display = base score + combo + multiplier +
flash + interpolation. Add or subtract any layer.

**Orchestration.** Frame order: input, score/combo update, decay check,
interpolate displayed-score, paint. Interpolation MUST come after
score update so the interpolation targets the current value.

**In-routing.** Hits route to score-bump handlers. Combo timer routes
frame-tick to decay checker. All routing is state-mutation via `set!`.

**Routing.** Score routes to display (as text). Score also routes to
Cortex (as persistent state). Two routes for one variable.

---

## 13.7 Common desktop tasks

**Shop-progress badge.** Customer completes an action (browse 5 items,
add to wishlist, share). Small score bumps for each; combo bonus if
done in one session. Score routes to a badge on the customer's
profile.

**Support-response streak.** Operator answering customer messages. Each
reply within 60 seconds of receipt = combo. Weekly streak leaderboard
among the operator's team. Score routes to team dashboard.

---

## 13.8 Pitfalls

**Score wraps at max integer.** Motoi Scheme uses bignums; you won't
hit this. But if you display formatted, large numbers get unreadable.
Format as `1.2M` beyond a million.

**Displayed-score never catches up.** Interpolation factor too small.
Try 0.15 or 0.2 for snappier.

**Combo breaks silently.** Kid doesn't know why. Add a visual: on
combo-break, brief red flash of the combo counter, then it vanishes.

**Multiplier resets on death.** By design, mostly. But some players
appreciate keeping their multiplier through respawn. Design choice.

---

## 13.9 Try this yourself

1. Cap max combo at 30 with a visual 'MAX!' banner when reached.
2. Add per-enemy score: small enemy 100, medium 300, large 800.
3. Streak bonus: after 10-combo, every point scores +50 as flat bonus.
4. Rank grade: at end of session, compute grade S/A/B/C/D from score.
5. Combo pause: 'b' button freezes decay for 2 seconds. Once per game.
6. Score sharing: on new high score, `paint-text` a share URL that
   encodes the score in a Cortex key.

---

## 13.10 What we built

Base score. Combo with decay window. Multiplier scaling. Interpolated
display. Screen flash on hit. Cortex persistence. All in about 40
lines of scoring logic.

Next chapter: wrap the game in the cabinet. Title screen. Play. Game
over. High score entry. Attract mode. The state machine of a full
arcade session.")

